commentBody:
@DQ You may not have had any fun, personally I enjoyed it very much and I'm sure many others did too. 
It makes me sad that this is the top-rated comment. Those of us who relish a really tough puzzle don't come here every week and complain when yet another Saturday succumbs in less than 20 minutes.
Please let us have our fun today; I'm sure normal service will resume again next week!

@Tryer 

Agree. How nice it must be to meet the person you admire most in the world and realize it is … YOU!

Please don’t play it again, Sam

@Jane 

This is Sam’s 55th NYT crossword puzzle.  His first was in 2012.  As Caitlin notes in her article, he is well-respected by people who solve crossword puzzles with much greater facility than any, or at least the vast majority, of us in this forum, as exemplified by the annual ACPT’s use of his puzzles.  

You might not like this puzzle, but telling Sam to stick to the Spelling Bee ignores the fact that he’s been constructing Xword puzzles long before your streak started and that many solvers, including me, eagerly look forward to his puzzles, even if THALAMI almost threw me into the Mississippi.

@Jones 

As I just said to Terry in VT, the dictionaries list UH-OH as one hyphenated word.

And the fact that it's in all the dictionaries is proof that it is a word.

@Nat K 
I am in awe of people like you that managed this puzzle without Googling.  As I read the comments, I'm learning that there are more of you than I thought there would be.
My hat off to you.  (But today I am wearing a hoodie, and the hoodie stays on!)

@Shan 

Wow, that is indeed a terrifying statistic! A little over 60 ppm increase in the 50 years between your birth date and Thunberg's -- and about the same in only the 20 years between her birth date and today. 😬  That really resonates with me!

By contrast, I love the anecdote about generational storytelling in your family. Thanks for sharing. ☺️

@Adam 

Pro tip: Don't try to use "UHOH" in Spelling Bee. :-)

(Been there, done that; as have, I'm sure, the emus.)

@Steve 
A word with a hyphen is considered one word, but hyphens are not allowed in Spelling Bee.

......................................

@Lpr 

Thank you for the gift link!  I wish the constructor had been as thoughtful when linking it in the wordplay column.  :(

Very glad to hear Mr. Shortz is on the mend.  Reportedly there's no no expected timeline yet but after today's puzzle I'm anxiously awaiting the return of his steady and reasoned hand.  :)

@Sarah 
It was a hard puzzle to be sure. (Took me much longer than usual to complete!)

But my view is that the "not-quite-right" clues are deliberately meant to misdirect, requiring one to reread them and rethink what they could mean. The ambiguities of language come to the fore, which I find to be a good thing.

@Withnail 

With a 700+ streak, it’s not likely that one puzzle is going to change your average by much.

Today’s puzzle took me more than twice as long as most Saturdays. I have a screenshot of my stats from the beginning of February, and my Saturday average is now one second longer than it was then.

@Frank 

I always picture Charlie Brown saying GAH when Lucy moves the football away just as he tries to kick it. 😂







YMMV, emus. 🦶🏈💥

@Maddie Yes, that was one tough puzzle and I had to take a couple of tries before i could solve it, and even then I needed a little help.

I didn't think of Dr. Stangelove at the time but now that you mention it, sure, it's Peter Sellers as President Merkin Muffley on the phone to the Russian premier trying to avert a nuclear war.

The People's Central Air Defense Headquarters... Where is that, Dmitri?... In Omsk... Right... Yes... Oh, you'll call them first, will you?... Uh-huh... Listen, do you happen to have the phone number on you, Dmitri?... Whe-ah, what? I see, just ask for Omsk information...

@Allen

The constructor/editors could have fixed it by just tweaking the clue to say 'utterance' or something instead of 'word'... I had "oops" first as well, actually I think I had both "oops" and "oH OH" (a common spelling) in the squares at the same time (a neat tip from someone many months ago here in Comments has been useful: when I think two or even three answers are equally plausible I'll sometimes rebus in both alternatives!). Didn't notice the single-word aspect of the clue so I thought oH-OH was a good possibility but I had it spelled with that "o" for quite a while...

Doing Sunday's puzzle— just finished an hour ago— was kind of a palate cleanser. Or pate cleanser.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

Haha!  Had OOPS at first.  Took me a long time to acknowledge that uh-oh is one word. 
Especially like HELP and WHEE.

@Andrzej 

Trace ADKINS is a country singer, and since that's the genre I listen to the most, I put it in rather quickly.  I'm sure it gave even Americans who don't listen to the genre trouble.  Here's one of my favorite Trace ADKINS songs; listen carefully to the lyrics:

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IORz6eS2qt0" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IORz6eS2qt0</a>

@Lori

“Hill” refers to Capital Hill in Washington, DC, where the US legislature is located.

😊

@Kelly,

Yes — exactly. But because of the deliberate ambiguity of “Cleveland” (the city? one of its major league sports teams? etc) the clue was worthy of a Saturday. 

I thought this was the best clue I have seen for the ubiquitous DEM, and nicely paired with Grant and Benjamin below it.

@Jim 
It's shocking how many people in this comment section refuse to accept that UH-OH is one hyphenated word.  😄

........................................

@Pax Ahimsa Gethen 

As far as I know, ALTA is the last resort that bans snowboards. Is it snobbish? Probably. Will they eventually cave in? Likely. 

We planned to go there in January despite the fact that my husband boards. He was willing to take a ski lesson, but when we learned that Alta only offers group lessons in the afternoon, it wasn’t a viable option.

@Seward Parker 

Yeah, I don't worry about seconds. 

Plus I'm typing on my phone, which makes me stingy with characters sometimes.

@dutchiris 

when the 'answer' for "Troy setting, for short" isn't actually short -- to give just one example of the too-clever-by-half clues in this puzzle -- it's garbage, in my book. 

you don't like my book? don't read it.

@LJADZ 

You can comfort yourself by thinking Sam had to Google words, too, but this is a professional word game editor we're talking about. I'd be willing to bet he didn't.

Although I enjoyed a lot of the wordplay, this puzzle was hard for me - took me way over my usual time. I'm not blaming that on anyone but myself.  Sam's cluing was reasonable, just very tough.
